### BUG-5: `TrashCleanupScheduler` uses wrong timestamp for auto-purge
**File**: [`TrashCleanupScheduler.java`](file:///c:/Users/Anmol%20Raj/OneDrive/Desktop/Java%20Project/src/main/java/com/cloudnest/service/TrashCleanupScheduler.java#L37)

**Exact Issue**:
```java
List<FileEntity> expired = fileRepository.findByIsDeletedTrueAndUploadedAtBefore(cutoff);
```
This queries against `uploadedAt` (the **upload date**), not the **deletion date**. A file uploaded 31 days ago but deleted yesterday will be **permanently purged by the next cleanup run** — even though it's only been in the trash for 1 day. This is data loss.

**Fix**: Add a `deletedAt` timestamp field to `FileEntity`:
```java
// In FileEntity.java — add:
@Column(name = "deleted_at")
private LocalDateTime deletedAt;

// In FileStorageService.deleteFile():
fileEntity.setDeleted(true);
fileEntity.setDeletedAt(LocalDateTime.now()); // record when it was trashed

// In FileRepository:
List<FileEntity> findByIsDeletedTrueAndDeletedAtBefore(LocalDateTime cutoff);

// In TrashCleanupScheduler:
List<FileEntity> expired = fileRepository.findByIsDeletedTrueAndDeletedAtBefore(cutoff);
```
Also add `deleted_at TIMESTAMP` column to `schema.sql`.

